From the formula booklet we can find the formula for a general term of the expansion

$$
\begin{align*}
    (a+b)^n&=...+\binom{n}{r}a^{n-r}b^r+...
\end{align*}
$$

Using the general term above, we can write an expression for the $x^3$ term and the $x^4$ term.

$$
\begin{align*}
    &\binom{6}{3}(a)^3(bx)^3& \binom{6}{4}(a)^2(bx)^4 \tag*{\textbf{A1A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can now use the information given to write an equation linking the coefficients of the two expressions above.

$$
\begin{align*}
    &\binom{6}{3}a^3b^3=-2\times \binom{6}{4}a^2b^4 \tag*{\textbf{M1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Using the formula we can evaluate the binomial coefficients and simplify

$$
\begin{align*}
    \textcolor{white}{hack} \tag*{\textbf{M1}}
\end{align*}
$$


$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{6!}{3!3!}a^3b^3&=-2\times \frac{6!}{4!2!}a^2b^4\\[6pt]
    \frac{6\times 5 \times 4\times \cancel{3!}}{\cancel{3!}\times3\times 2\times 1}a^3b^3&=-2\times \frac{6\times 5 \times  \cancel{4!}}{\cancel{4!}\times 2 \times 1}a^2b^4\\[6pt]
    20a^3b^3&=-30a^2b^4 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We need to find the value of $\tfrac{a}{b}$ therefore we can rearrange the expression above

$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{a^3b^3}{a^2b^4}&=\frac{-30}{20}\\[6pt]
    \frac{a}{b}&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\frac{-3}{2}}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
    &=-1.5
\end{align*}
$$

First we will unpack the sigma notation.
The smallest value of $k$ is $\textcolor{red}{a}$. This value is the increased by $1$ for each subsequent term.

$$
\begin{align*}
    \sum_{k=a}^{a+35} \log_{13} \left(\frac{k+1}{k}\right)&=\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a}}\right)+\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+1}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+1}}\right)+\\[6pt]
    &\hspace{1.2em}\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+2}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+2}}\right)+...
\end{align*}
$$

This continues until we reach the largest value of $k$ which is $a+35$.

$$
\begin{align*}
    +...\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+34}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+34}}\right)+\log_{13} \left(\frac{\textcolor{red}{a+35}+1}{\textcolor{red}{a+35}}\right) \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

If we simplify the fractions and then apply the following log law

$$
\begin{align*}
    \log_{a}\tfrac{x}{y}&=\log_{a}x-\log_{a}y
\end{align*}
$$

We get

$$
\begin{align*}
    \sum_{k=a}^{a+35} \log_{13} \left(\frac{k+1}{k}\right)&=\log_{13} \left(\frac{a+1}{a}\right)+\log_{13} \left(\frac{a+2}{a+1}\right)+...\log_{13} \left(\frac{a+36}{a+35}\right)\\[6pt]
    &=\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+1)}}-\textcolor{blue}{\log_{13}{a}}+\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+2)}}-\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+1)}}+\\[6pt]
    &\hspace{1.2em}-\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+2)}}+...+\textcolor{blue}{\log_{13}{(a+36)}}-\cancel{\log_{13}{(a+35)}} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

Notice how the terms cancel each other out, leaving only the two $\textcolor{blue}{\text{blue}}$ terms. Recall, from the question, this is equal to $1$.

$$
\begin{align*}
    -\log_{13}{a}+\log_{13}{(a+36)}&=1 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can now solve the equation by rewriting the L.H.S. as a single logarithm

$$
\begin{align*}
    \log_{13}{\left(\frac{a+36}{a}\right)}&=1
\end{align*}
$$

Using the definition of a logarithm, we rewrite the equation into exponential form

$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{a+36}{a}&=13^1 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Now we can solve for $a$

$$
\begin{align*}
    a+36&=13a\\[6pt]
    12a&=36\\[6pt]
    &\hspace{-0.8em}\answer{a=3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

- The area of a trapezium formula requires the lengths of the two parallel sides and the perpendicular distance between them.


![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/679151b0-9bb0-41ea-bd04-7ee3212a82ef/images/5195ca90-7dcd-434c-b82c-e98f6c0423b6/AA1158_a.JPEG)


$h$ is distance between the sides $AB$ and $CD$ and $x$ is half of $CD$.
Therefore we can write

$$
\begin{align*}
    A&=\left(\tfrac{2x+2r}{2}\right)h\\[6pt]
    &=\left(x+r\right)h
\end{align*}
$$

Using the trigonometric ratios we can write

$$
\begin{align*}
    x&=r\cos{\theta}\\[6pt]
    h&=r\sin{\theta} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
\end{align*}
$$

Using those results we can write $A$ in terms of $r$ and $\theta$.

$$
\begin{align*}
A&=\left(r\cos{\theta}+r\right)r\sin{\theta}\tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[6pt]
&=r^2(\cos{\theta}\sin{\theta}+\sin{\theta})\\[6pt]
&=r^2(\tfrac{1}{2}\sin{2\theta}+\sin{\theta})\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
A&=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\tfrac{1}{2}r^2(\sin{2\theta}+2\sin{\theta})} \hspace{2em}\text{...as required}
\end{align*}
$$

- To find the maximum area we should differentiate $A$ with respect to $\theta$ treating $r$ as a constant.

$$
\begin{align*}
    \frac{\mathrm{d}A}{\mathrm{d}\theta}&=\tfrac{1}{2}r^2\left(2\cos{2\theta+2\cos{\theta}}\right)\tag*{\textbf{M1}}
\end{align*}
$$

At the maximum value $\frac{\mathrm{d}A}{\mathrm{d}\theta}=0$, therefore

$$
\begin{align*}
    0&=\tfrac{1}{2}r^2\left(2\cos{2\theta}+2\cos{\theta}\right)\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[6pt]
    0&=2\cos{2\theta}+2\cos{\theta}&\hspace{2em}&\text{as }r\text{ is a constant and }r>0\\[6pt]
    0&=2(2\cos^2{\theta}-1)+2\cos{\theta}\\[6pt]
    0&=2\cos^2{\theta}-1+\cos{\theta}\tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}\\[6pt]
    &=(2\cos{\theta}-1)(\cos{\theta}+1)\\[6pt]
    \cos{\theta}&=\tfrac{1}{2}&\hspace{-6em}&\cos{\theta}=-1&\\[6pt]
    \theta&=\tfrac{\pi}{3}&&\hspace{1.7em}\theta=\pi&\tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
\end{align*}
$$

Therefore the maximum value of $A$ must occur when $\theta = \frac{\pi}{3}$ as $\theta<\tfrac{\pi}{2}$.
Hence

$$
\begin{align*}
    A_{\text{max}}&=\tfrac{1}{2}r^2(\sin{\left(\tfrac{2\pi}{3}\right)}+2\sin{\left(\tfrac{\pi}{3}\right)})\\[6pt]
    &=\tfrac{1}{2}r^2\left(\tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}+2\times \tfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)\\[6pt]
    &=\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{\frac{3\sqrt{3}}{4}r^2} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

