$$
\begin{align*}
    &=6-\left[\tfrac{1}{12}(x-2)^3+2x\right]_{2}^{4}\\[12pt]
    &=6-\left[\left(\tfrac{1}{12}(4-2)^3+2\times 4\right)-\left(\tfrac{1}{12}(2-2)^3+2\times 2\right)\right]\\[12pt]
    &=6-\left[\left(\tfrac{8}{12}+8\right)-4\right]\\[12pt]
    &=6-\left(\tfrac{2}{3}+4\right)\\[12pt]
    &=\tfrac{4}{3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We can find the area of $L$ in a similar way

$$
\begin{align*}
    A_L&=\left[\tfrac{1}{12}(x-2)^3+2x\right]_{2}^{4}-4 \tag*{\textbf{M1}}\\[12pt]
    &=\left(\tfrac{2}{3}+4\right)-4\\[12pt]
    &=\tfrac{2}{3} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Therefore $\hspace{0.525em}\answer{A_U=2\times A_L}\hspace{0.525em}$ as required.
- Here is a sketch of the new rectangle with the variable point $C$.


![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/51c5c963-7f0e-489b-8337-0d8c9be7a46a/images/9aef0f17-1937-4997-8fff-b063bf416d63/AA1160_q%20(1).JPEG)


Let the area of the new rectangle be $A_{R}$.
The width of the rectangle is $b-2$ and the height is $f(b)-2$, hence

$$
\begin{align*}
    A_{R}&=(f(b)-2)(b-2)\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[6pt]
    &=(\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^2+2-2)(b-2)\\[6pt]
    &=\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^2(b-2)\\[6pt]
    &=\hspace{0.525em}\answer{\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^3}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

- Using the answer to part (b) we can write

$$
\begin{align*}
    \int_{2}^{b}f(x)\,\mathrm{d}x&=\left[\tfrac{1}{12}(x-2)^3+2x\right]_{2}^{b}\\[6pt]
    &=\left(\tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3+2b\right)-\left(\tfrac{1}{12}(2-2)^3+2\times 2\right)\\[6pt]
    &=\answer{\tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3+2b-4} \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

- Consider the red rectangle shown in the following image


![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/51c5c963-7f0e-489b-8337-0d8c9be7a46a/images/63cfeb1a-27bb-4087-bdf2-258ed0912167/AA1160_a3.JPEG)


Using our answer from part (a) we can evaluate $f(b$) and see that the area of the red rectangle in terms of $b$ is

$$
\begin{align*}
    (b-2)f(b)&=(b-2)\left(\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^2+2\right)\\[6pt]
    &=\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^3+2(b-2)\\[6pt]
    &=\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^3+2b-4 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Using the answer from part (f) we can now write an expression for the area of region $U$

$$
\begin{align*}
A_U&=\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^3+2b-4 - \int_{2}^{b}f(x)\,\mathrm{d}x\\[6pt]
&=\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^3+2b-4 - \left(\tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3+2b-4\right)\\[6pt]
&=\tfrac{1}{4}(b-2)^3\cancel{+2b-4} - \tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3\cancel{-2b+4}\\[6pt]
&=\tfrac{1}{6}(b-2)^3 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

Consider the blue rectangle shown in the image below


![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/51c5c963-7f0e-489b-8337-0d8c9be7a46a/images/da97556d-ae72-478d-ae35-6f858c291fa6/AA1160_a4.JPEG)


We can see that the area is

$$
\begin{align*}
    2(b-2)&=2b-4
\end{align*}
$$

We can find the area of region $L$ by subtracting the area of the blue triangle from the area under the curve.

$$
\begin{align*}
    A_L&=\int_{2}^{b}f(x)\,\mathrm{d}x - (2b-4)\\[6pt]
    &=\left(\tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3+2b-4\right)-(2b-4)\\[6pt]
    &=\tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3\cancel{+2b-4}\cancel{-2b+4}\\[6pt]
    &=\tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
\end{align*}
$$

We now have expressions for $A_U$ and $A_L$ in terms of $b$, which is the $x-$coordinate of point $C$. Hence

$$
\begin{align*}
    \tfrac{1}{6}(b-2)^3&=2 \times \tfrac{1}{12}(b-2)^3 \tag*{\textbf{A1}}\\[6pt]
    A_U&=2 \times A_L
\end{align*}
$$

Hence,
$\answer{\text{The area of region }U\text{ is twice the area of region }L\text{ for any position of point C.}}$
